{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640038","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640038"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:11:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:11:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17795"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17795","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17795"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.91,0,0.03,0.03,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10509"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73242"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10509","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10509"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17795"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58713"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9932"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24533"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25014"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73242","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73242"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EProprioceptors in the respiratory system play a crucial role in monitoring and regulating breathing patterns.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the function of pulmonary stretch receptors?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Monitor lung inflation and inhibit further inspiration","Sense airway muscle fatigue","Detect airway irritants and trigger coughing","Measure blood carbon dioxide levels","Monitor blood oxygen saturation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary stretch receptors monitor lung inflation and inhibit further inspiration\u003C/strong\u003E through the Hering-Breuer reflex. These slowly adapting mechanoreceptors are located in airway smooth muscle and respond to changes in lung volume. When activated by lung inflation, they send signals via the vagus nerve to the respiratory centre in the brainstem, inhibiting further inspiration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetect airway irritants and trigger coughing\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the function of irritant receptors in the airways\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeasure blood carbon dioxide levels\u003C/strong\u003E - This is performed by central and peripheral chemoreceptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESense airway muscle fatigue\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not a specific function of any known respiratory receptor\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMonitor blood oxygen saturation\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the role of peripheral chemoreceptors in the carotid and aortic bodies\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Hering-Breuer reflex is particularly important in preventing over-inflation of the lungs during normal breathing, though it may be less active in adult humans during quiet breathing.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pulmonary stretch receptors in airway smooth muscle respond to lung inflation and trigger the Hering-Breuer reflex.","The Hering-Breuer reflex helps prevent over-inflation of the lungs by inhibiting inspiration when lung volume increases.","Pulmonary stretch receptors are slowly adapting mechanoreceptors that monitor lung volume changes."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021. https://clinicalkeymeded.elsevier.com/reader/books/9780323597128"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58713"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17795"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58713","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58713"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T09:41:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T09:43:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10509"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73242"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4927"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respirat